borders_help_text_eng = [
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Cadastre Map</strong><br><br>The cadastre map is a visual representation of cadastral data, depicting the boundaries, sizes, and locations of registered land parcels in Estonia. <br>The map layer provides the most up-to-date information on the general data of cadastral units registered in the cadastre. The cadastral boundaries in the map application are informative. <br>For a more detailed overview of land units, visit the page minu.kataster.ee<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>State Forests</strong><br><br>Estonian state forests are part of Estonias forestry system, managed and overseen by RMK (State Forest Management Centre). The primary goal of state forests is to provide a range of ecological, economic, and social services. These forests cover approximately 1.1 million hectares, which constitutes about 50% of Estonias forested land.<br><br>On this map, areas outlined in black are state-owned.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Private Forests Map</strong><br><br>Private forests in Estonia are forest lands owned and managed by private individuals or forest cooperatives. These forests cover approximately 500,000 hectares, which constitutes about 25% of Estonias forest area.<br><br>On this map, the areas outlined in black are private forests.<br><br> <strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Protected Areas Map</strong><br><br>In Estonia, protected areas are established to preserve biodiversity and protect endangered species. Protected areas are divided into several categories, each with its own objectives and protection requirements. The main types of protected areas in Estonia are:<br><br><strong>National Parks</strong>:<br>National parks are the largest and most strictly protected areas, aiming to preserve and introduce the typical and outstanding values of the estonian natural and cultural heritage. <br>Examples: Lahemaa National Park, Soomaa National Park, Matsalu National Park, Vilsandi National Park, and Karula National Park.<br><br><strong>Nature Reserves</strong>:<br>These areas are established to protect rare, endangered, or scientifically valuable species, communities, or geological features. <br>Examples: Endla Nature Reserve, Nigula Nature Reserve, Vilsandi Nature Reserve.<br><br><strong>Landscape Protection Areas</strong>:<br>These areas are established to protect and preserve distinctive landscape values. The aim is to preserve and restore natural and semi-natural communities and landscape elements. <br>Examples: Otepää Landscape Protection Area, Haanja Landscape Protection Area, Naissaar Landscape Protection Area.<br><br><strong>Conservation Zones</strong>:<br>These are established to preserve the habitats and ecosystems of rare and endangered species. Conservation measures are applied to ensure the preservation and recovery of habitats. <br>Examples: Alam-Pedja Nature Reserve, Silma Nature Reserve.<br><br><strong>Permanent Habitats</strong>:<br>These are smaller areas focused on the protection of specific rare or endangered species and their habitats. <br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Protected Forest</strong><br><br>A protected forest can be located in a protected area, around a protected natural object, in a coastal restriction zone, or in a conservation area. Examples of protected forests include recreational areas, forest parks, and park forests, urban green belt forests and green area stands, forests along roads and railways, high-yield berry and mushroom forests, coastal forests, forests in monument protection zones, and spring areas.<br><br>This map layer shows protected forests in areas bounded by light blue lines.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>https://kah-alad.ee/moisted/kaitsemets/<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Notices Map</strong><br><br>A forest certificate is a document required by the Forest Act that forest owners must submit to the Environment Board in order to carry out felling operations.All forest declarations submitted to the Environment Board are processed and stored in the National Forest Register. <br><br><strong>SR</strong> - Sanitary felling, removal of trees damaged by diseases, pests, or storms to prevent the spread of pests and diseases.<br><br><strong>LR</strong> - Clear-cutting, all trees are cut in a specific area at once to promote the growth of a new generation of forest.<br><br><strong>HR</strong> - Thinning, performed to reduce tree density, allowing the remaining trees to grow and develop better.<br><br><strong>AR</strong> - Shelterwood cutting, the forest is cut gradually in several stages to ensure continuous regeneration and maintain forest cover.<br><br><strong>HL</strong> - Gap cutting, performed in the form of small clearings (gaps) to promote natural regeneration and diversity.<br><br><strong>VR</strong> - Selection cutting, individual trees are selected and cut, maintaining a continuous presence of trees of different ages and sizes in the forest.<br><br><strong>VE</strong> - Strip cutting, trees are cut in narrow strips to promote natural regeneration and reduce soil damage.<br><br><strong>RD</strong> - Land clearing, forest land is completely cleared of trees, usually in preparation for other land uses such as agriculture or construction.<br><br><strong>TR</strong> - Line cutting, trees are cut in narrow areas to establish routes such as roads, power lines, or pipelines.<br><br><strong>KR</strong> - Shaping cutting, felling works aimed at improving the aesthetic appearance of the forest and landscaping.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Field Map</strong><br><br>This map shows the boundaries of fields in Estonia and the unique number of each field.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Contour Lines Map</strong><br><br>A line connecting points at the same elevation above sea level. Typically, contour lines with the same elevation difference are used on the map, e.g., 2 or 5 meters apart. As a result, the horizontal distance between the lines indicates the slope steepness.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>https://wiki.estgis.ee/index.php?title=Contour_Line<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Base Map of Estonia</strong><br><br>The base map of Estonia at 1:10,000 scale is a large-scale digital topographic map produced from the Estonian Topographic Database (ETAK) data.<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>Soil Map</strong><br><br><strong>Soil types found in Estonia</strong>:<br><br><strong>Tz</strong> Buried soil<br><strong>Kh</strong> Limestone soil<br><strong>Tzg</strong> Gleyed buried soil<br><strong>Kr</strong> Coarse-grained rendzina soil<br><strong>Gor</strong> Coarse-grained leached gley soil<br><strong>K</strong> Rendzina soil<br><strong>Go</strong> Leached gley soil<br><strong>Kk</strong> Gravelly soil<br><strong>GI</strong> Podzolic gley soil<br><strong>Kor</strong> Coarse-grained leached soil<br><strong>LPG</strong> Albic gley soil<br><strong>Ko</strong> Leached soil<br><strong>LkG</strong> Albic gley soil<br><strong>KI</strong> Podzolic soil<br><strong>LG</strong> Podzol-gley soil<br><strong>Gh1</strong> Limestone peaty soil<br><strong>Go1</strong> Saturated peaty soil<br><strong>GI1</strong> Unsaturated peaty soil<br><strong>LG1</strong> Podzol-peaty soil<br><strong>M</strong> Fen soil<br><strong>S</strong> Transitional bog soil<br><strong>R</strong> Bog soil<br><strong>E2k</strong> Moderately eroded rendzina soil<br><strong>E2o</strong> Moderately eroded leached and podzolic soil<br><strong>E2I</strong> Moderately eroded albic podzolic and podzolic soil<br><strong>E3k</strong> Strongly eroded rendzina soil<br><strong>E3o</strong> Strongly eroded leached and podzolic soil<br><strong>E3I</strong> Strongly eroded albic podzolic and podzolic soil<br><strong>D</strong> Deluvial soil<br><strong>Dg</strong> Gleyed deluvial soil<br><strong>DG</strong> Deluvial gley soil<br><strong>Ag</strong> Gleyed alluvial soil<br><strong>AG</strong> Alluvial gley soil<br><strong>AG1</strong> Alluvial peaty soil<br><strong>AM</strong> Alluvial fen soil<br><strong>Ar</strong> Saline primitive soil<br><strong>ArG</strong> Saline gley soil<br><strong>ArG1</strong> Saline peaty soil<br><strong>Arv</strong> Saline underwater soil<br><strong>Gr</strong> Coastal gley soil<br><strong>Gr1</strong> Coastal peaty soil<br><strong>Mr</strong> Coastal fen soil<br><strong>Av</strong> Underwater soil<br><strong>TzG</strong> Buried gley soil<br><strong>TzM</strong> Buried fen soil<br><strong>TZR</strong> Buried bog soil<br><strong>AvG</strong> Underwater gley soil<br><strong>AvM</strong> Underwater fen soil<br><strong>AvR</strong> Underwater bog soil<br><br><strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>Estonian Land Board<br>'
]

