'<strong style=font-size:20px;>RGB</strong><br><br>Standard orthophoto - RGB represents the three primary colors – red (Red), green (Green), and blue (Blue) – which can be combined in various ways to display the entire color spectrum. The intensity of each color is measured on a scale from 0 to 255, allowing for the creation of more than 16 million different color shades.<br><br> <strong style=font-size:20px;>Source:</strong><br>https://geoportaal.maaamet.ee/geoportaal.maaamet.ee/est/ruumiandmed/ortofotod-p99.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NRG (NIR-Red-Green) False Color Image</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>This false color image can also be referred to as a winter forestry image. In this false color image, reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR), red light (Red), and green light (Green) are combined. The information from the near-infrared radiation is placed in the visible spectrums red channel, the red visible radiation information in the green channel, and the green light spectrum information in the blue channel.<br><br><strong>Plant Reflection Properties</strong><br>Chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation and green light well. Plants reflect near-infrared radiation most intensely, and since we display this through the red channel, the vegetation appears red in the image.<br><br><strong>Deciduous and Coniferous Trees</strong><br>Brighter reds represent deciduous trees, while darker reds represent coniferous trees, which reflect less near-infrared radiation. As deciduous trees lose their green color and shed their leaves in autumn, we can also see this difference in satellite images. Coniferous trees, being evergreen, remain cherry-red in the satellite false color image, while areas with bare trees appear green.<br><br><strong>Bare and Damaged Trees</strong><br>Photosynthesizing plants reflect near-infrared radiation, green, and a small amount of red light. However, in the case of bare or damaged trees, the reflection of green and near-infrared radiation is very low or absent, and the reflection of red light significantly increases. Since we display red light through the green channel in this false color image combination, bare or vegetation-poor areas appear green. The NRG combination also highlights tree shadows well.<br><br><strong>Agricultural Fields and Grasslands</strong><br>Bright reds or pinks represent agricultural fields and grasslands with higher or denser vegetation cover. Areas without vegetation appear green. While soil does reflect near-infrared radiation, the greater contribution of red light causes bare soil to appear light green. As a result, mowed grasslands and peat fields appear light green in the NGR false color image.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/nrg-nir-red-green-p5.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NDVI</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>NDVI is a computational vegetation index that is convenient for assessing vegetation density and plant health. Chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation (NIR) and green light (G) well but absorbs red light (R). NDVI allows for the assessment of the difference between reflected near-infrared radiation and red radiation using the following formula: NDVI = (NIR – R) / (NIR + R).<br><br><strong>NDVI Values</strong><br>If the NDVI value of an area is positive, it appears green in the image. The higher the NDVI value, the greener and denser the vegetation. If the vegetation is sparse, more red light is reflected than near-infrared radiation. If the corresponding NDVI value is negative, the area appears red in the image. Such areas have sparse vegetation or plants under stress.<br><br><strong>Clouds and Artificial Surfaces</strong><br>Clouds also reflect more red light than near-infrared radiation, making them appear red in the image. Some thinner clouds may appear yellow. Artificial surfaces range in color from yellow to red.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ndvi-p6.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NGR</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>In the NGR false color image, reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR), green light (Green), and red light (Red) are combined. The information from the near-infrared radiation is placed in the visible spectrums red channel, the green visible radiation information in the green channel, and the red light spectrum information in the blue channel.<br><br><strong>Plant Reflection Properties</strong><br>Chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation and green light well. On a false color image, this would mean a combination of red and green light, which in the RGB model appears orange. Since deciduous trees reflect near-infrared radiation more intensely than coniferous trees, they can be easily distinguished by color.<br><br><strong>Forests</strong><br>Deciduous forests appear as textured dark orange, while coniferous forests are dark green. Therefore, the NGR image provides a good overview of forest composition.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ngr-p7.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NDPI</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>NDPI is a computational water body index used to assess vegetation water content. It is determined by comparing reflected shortwave infrared radiation (SWIR) with reflected green light (G).<br><br><strong>NDPI Values</strong><br>If an area reflects more green light than shortwave infrared radiation, the index value is negative. On the map, such areas range from blue to dark blue. This color typically represents water bodies and water-saturated vegetation.<br><br><strong>Detection Limitations</strong><br>It should be noted that while NDPI is quite effective for detecting surface water and water-saturated vegetation, its detection is limited to a thin layer of the earths surface and appears most valid when vegetation is green. Additionally, there are certain limitations related to wetlands.<br><br><strong>Winter Use</strong><br>In winter, the filter can help assess which areas are covered with snow and which are not. Snow-covered areas appear blue, while snow-free areas are yellow.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ndpi-p8.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>PNB</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The PNB false color image combines a computational water body index (NDPI), reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR), and blue light.<br><br><strong>Plant Reflection Properties</strong><br>Chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation well, but significantly less blue light. Healthy plants also have a low NDPI value, indicating sufficient water content. Therefore, areas with healthy vegetation appear green in the image. Light green areas indicate high chlorophyll content and sufficient water, such as in unmown fields and deciduous trees. Coniferous trees reflect slightly less near-infrared radiation compared to deciduous trees, making them appear brownish-green in the image.<br><br><strong>Mown Fields and Areas Without Vegetation</strong><br>Mown fields appear bright pink because the soil is exposed, having a high NDPI value but reflecting less light in the near-infrared and blue spectrum. The pink color indicates a significant contribution from the blue channel, as its influence is strongest in this filter. Fields with sparse vegetation appear dark blue due to the visible soil between plants.<br><br><strong>Peat Fields and Bogs</strong><br>Peat fields have a high NDPI value, reflecting little blue light and near-infrared radiation, causing them to appear red. Bogs also share this color tone.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies and Clouds</strong><br>Water bodies generally have a low NDPI value and absorb near-infrared radiation well. They reflect minimal blue light, making them dark blue in the image. Clouds reflect both near-infrared radiation and blue light, with a low NDPI value, resulting in a light blue color.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/pnb-p9.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NGP</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The NGP false color image combines reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR), green light, and a computational water body index (NDPI).<br><br><strong>Plant Reflection Properties</strong><br>Chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation and green light well. Healthy plants also have a low NDPI value, indicating sufficient water content. Therefore, areas with vegetation appear in shades of yellow to orange in the image. Dark orange areas indicate high chlorophyll content and sufficient water, such as in unmown fields and deciduous trees. Coniferous trees reflect slightly less near-infrared radiation compared to deciduous trees, making them appear dark green in the image.<br><br><strong>Mown Fields and Areas Without Vegetation</strong><br>Mown fields appear light blue due to exposed soil with a high NDPI value. Fields with sparse vegetation range in color from green to light blue, as the soil is visible between the plants.<br><br><strong>Peat Fields and Bogs</strong><br>Peat fields have a high NDPI value and reflect little green light, making them appear blue. Bogs share this color tone.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies and Clouds</strong><br>Water bodies generally have a low NDPI value and absorb near-infrared radiation well. They reflect minimal green light, appearing dark green in the image. Clouds, however, reflect both green light and near-infrared radiation, with a low NDPI value, making them appear yellow in the image. Snow is also yellow.<br><br><strong>Artificial Areas</strong><br>Artificial areas can be identified by their light green color.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ngp-p10.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NDR</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The NDR false color image combines reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR), red light, and a computational vegetation index (NDVI).<br><br><strong>Dense Vegetation</strong><br>The vegetation index allows for the assessment of the density and health of the vegetation in the observed area. The higher the index value, the more greenery is present. Dense vegetation also reflects a lot of near-infrared radiation while reflecting little red light, as plants absorb it for photosynthesis. Therefore, areas with dense vegetation appear from green to yellow in the image. Fields and deciduous trees appear yellow, while coniferous trees reflect less near-infrared radiation and thus appear green.<br><br><strong>Sparse Vegetation</strong><br>Fields with sparse vegetation appear pink in the image. Mown fields range from purple to dark blue, as exposed soil reflects both red light and near-infrared radiation well. Peat fields and artificial areas are dark blue, while bogs appear dark purple.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies</strong><br>Water bodies absorb light well across the observed spectrum and have a low NDVI value. As a result, they appear black in the image.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ndr-p11.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>PDB</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The PDB false color image combines a computational water body index (NDPI), a vegetation index (NDVI), and blue light.<br><br><strong>NDVI and NDPI</strong><br>NDVI is used to assess the greenery of the observed area. The higher the NDVI value for an area, the denser and healthier the vegetation. NDPI is used to evaluate the water content of the vegetation. The higher the water content in the vegetation, the lower the NDPI value. Conversely, a higher NDPI value indicates that the area reflects more shortwave infrared radiation compared to green light.<br><br><strong>Vegetation Differences</strong><br>The image clearly highlights areas where the NDVI value is low and the NDPI value is high. For example, mown fields appear fuchsia pink, and peat fields appear red. Dense vegetation areas with a high NDVI value and low NDPI value appear green. Coniferous trees appear dark green, while deciduous trees appear slightly lighter green. Fields also appear light green.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies and Artificial Surfaces</strong><br>Water bodies absorb blue light well and have low NDVI and NDPI values, making them appear dark blue or black in the image. Artificial surfaces also appear dark blue.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/pdb-p12.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NDN</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The NDN false color image combines a computational vegetation index (NDVI) with reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR).<br><br><strong>Different Vegetation Areas</strong><br>The more greenery there is in the observed area, the higher the NDVI value. Additionally, greenery can also be assessed by measuring the reflected near-infrared radiation. Areas where the NDVI value is high and a lot of near-infrared radiation is reflected appear white in the image. These areas include unmown fields, which show up as white patches with clear boundaries. Deciduous forests also appear white. Coniferous forests reflect somewhat less near-infrared radiation, so they appear green. Areas of the field with minimal plant growth also appear green.<br>Distinctly visible are mown fields, which appear dark pink due to the high NDPI value of the soil. Peat fields are similar in color but somewhat duller. Artificial areas also appear pink but are more vibrant compared to peat fields.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies and Clouds</strong><br>Water bodies appear black in the image as water reflects very little near-infrared radiation. Clouds appear pink as they reflect near-infrared radiation well.<br><br><strong>Winter Conditions</strong><br>In winter, snow appears pink because it reflects near-infrared radiation well. Areas not covered by thick snow appear green.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/ndn-p13.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>PDN</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The PDN false color image combines a computational water bodies index (NDPI), a vegetation index (NDVI), and reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR). This false color image is primarily intended for analyzing images taken during winter.<br><br><strong>Vegetation and Near-Infrared Radiation Assessment</strong><br>The vegetation index allows for evaluating the density and health of vegetation in an area. This is determined by the difference between reflected near-infrared radiation and red light. Chlorophyll in plants reflects more near-infrared radiation than red light. This helps to distinguish coniferous trees from bare trees.<br><br><strong>Different Vegetation Areas</strong><br>Coniferous trees are clearly visible and appear yellow in the image due to high NDVI and NDPI values. Areas with bare trees appear green. Snow appears dark blue in the image. In summer images, unmown fields and deciduous trees appear light blue, while coniferous trees appear green. This is because coniferous trees contain less chlorophyll compared to deciduous trees. Mown or bare areas appear red due to the exposure of soil, which reflects near-infrared radiation well, resulting in a high NDPI value. Peat fields are also orange or red.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies</strong><br>Water bodies appear black due to their very low NDPI and their strong absorption of near-infrared radiation.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/pdn-p14.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>NNR</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The NNR false color image combines reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR) and red light. Since chlorophyll in plants reflects near-infrared radiation and absorbs red light, the color of vegetated areas ranges from green to light yellow.<br><br><strong>Winter Conditions</strong><br>During winter, coniferous forests can be distinguished from bare trees. Coniferous trees reflect near-infrared radiation even in winter due to their evergreen nature, appearing green in the image. Areas with only bare trees appear blue. Snow reflects light well across the visible spectrum, so areas under thick snow cover appear white.<br><br><strong>Summer Conditions</strong><br>In summer, vegetation is denser, resulting in higher reflected near-infrared radiation. Thus, vegetated areas appear green, or even yellow in cases of very high chlorophyll content. Mown or bare areas appear blue due to the visibility of soil, which reflects both red light and near-infrared radiation. However, since the contribution of red light is higher in this image, soil appears blue. Peat bogs and wetlands also appear blue.<br><br><strong>Water Bodies</strong><br>Water bodies absorb light across the entire spectral range, making them appear black. This also makes the boundaries of water bodies clearly visible.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/nnr-p15.html',
'<strong style=font-size:20px;>DNP</strong><br><br><strong>Overview</strong><br>The DNP false color image combines the vegetation index (NDVI), the water index (NDPI), and reflected near-infrared radiation (NIR). The vegetation index helps assess the density and health of vegetation in an area, determined by the difference between reflected near-infrared radiation and red light. Chlorophyll in plants reflects more near-infrared radiation than red light.<br><br><strong>Vegetation and Fields</strong><br>Vegetated areas may appear red in the image, such as coniferous forests. Areas with high chlorophyll content, like broadleaf forests and unmown fields, appear yellow. Mown fields appear blue due to the visibility of soil, which has a high NDPI value.<br><br><strong>Peat Bogs and Water Bodies</strong><br>Peat bogs range in color from pink to dark blue. Bogs also appear pink. Water bodies appear black because they have minimal NDPI values and absorb near-infrared radiation effectively.<br><br><strong>Artificial Surfaces, Clouds, and Winter Conditions</strong><br>Artificial surfaces and clouds appear green in the image. In winter, snow appears green, while coniferous trees appear pink. Bare trees appear orange.<br><br><strong>Source</strong><br>https://ehwebtest.maaamet.ee/est/abi/dnp-p16.html',
''
